It is even more improbable that the treatises in question were composed, or so far reduced to order, at some period in the long interval which must'have elapsed between the author's conception of the Logarithms, and the construction of those elaborate works by which the glory of the invention was secured to himself, and the benefit bestowed upon mankind. In his book of Geometrical Logistic, Napier seems to allude to the Arithmetic of Surds as a discovery of his own, the full value of which he promises afterwards to disclose. Had he been conscious at this time of the far more important secret of the Logarithms,—which, after his first conception of the idea, was his daily labour to the end of his dayS,—there would, in all probability, have been some allusion to it.
